# HTML

Write clear, semantic, accessible markup from the first draft — not a monolith page to clean up later.

## Docs & comments

Spiritually the same bar as Python/JS: document purpose clearly, comment intent — never narrate obvious tags.

- Every HTML document starts with a short top-of-file comment describing the page’s purpose
- Section landmarks and non-obvious blocks get a brief comment when the structure isn’t clear from headings alone
- Comments only where intent is non-obvious — never label every `<div>` or restate visible heading text

```html
<!-- dashboard.html — Operator overview: status summary and recent jobs. -->

<main>
  <!-- Live status cards; values filled by dashboard.js -->
  <section aria-labelledby="status-heading">
    ...
  </section>
</main>
```

## Structure & semantics

- Prefer semantic elements (`main`, `nav`, `header`, `footer`, `section`, `article`, `button`, `label`) over generic `<div>` / `<span>` soup
- Give elements meaningful `id`s as often as practical (hooks for JS, CSS, tests, and deep links) — prefer stable, purpose-based names; keep them unique in the document
- One page, one `<h1>`; heading levels nest without skipping for outline clarity
- Keep structure organized: when a page grows, split into partials/templates/components using whatever the project already uses — don’t maintain a single giant HTML file if the stack supports composition
- Group related markup together; keep scripts and styles out of the markup when the project has external `.js` / `.css` (match existing patterns)
- Be reasonable: don’t invent a component framework for a static two-section page

## Accessibility & forms

- Interactive controls must be real `<button>`, `<a href>`, or form fields — not clickable `<div>`s
- Every form input has an associated `<label>` (or otherwise valid accessible name)
- Images that convey meaning get meaningful `alt`; decorative images get `alt=""`
- Use landmark roles only when native elements aren’t enough; prefer native semantics first
- Preserve keyboard focus order; don’t remove focus outlines without an accessible replacement

## Robustness & safety

- Produce valid HTML5; keep nesting and closing tags correct — treat markup errors like type errors
- Never place secrets, tokens, or credentials in HTML
- Escape/encode untrusted content; do not inject raw user HTML unless the project has a deliberate, sanitized pipeline
- Prefer external scripts with clear `type`/`defer`/`async` per project convention over large inline script blocks
- When behavior is non-trivial, pair the page with JS modules that follow the JavaScript/JSX rules (tested there — not with ad-hoc inline scripts)
